Friday - Rainy and dismal</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I woke up to gray skies and spitting rain. The bitter wind from the east was almost enough to make me reconsider my plan to hunt out in the plains for skins today. But as I pulled on my badly torn leggings and stuffed my toes into my tattered sandals, I knew what had to be done. The tracks were sparse, and the hunting sparser. It seems this plague has made the already small lion population dwindle even further. However, with perserverance I managed to skin half a dozen cats before noon and hung the pelts on stretchers to dry for tomorrow.<br>
<br>
I spent the good part of the afternoon getting dirty. After an hour under the docks, fishing and building castles out of the sand with a girl who claimed to be a mermaid with legs, I made my way to the forge and got the fires going. I've finally gotten used to my tools. It's been a few weeks practicing with the hammer, but after sharpening countless blades I have moved on to crafting things that will be of some use to me.<br>
<br>
After a while at the forge, a man approached me and began to ask me about what I was doing. We talked for a while, and before long we were chatting like old friends. He invited me for a drink at the local tavern and I went, glad for a break. It wasn't long before we were both fairly giddy, swapping stories of times passed and flirting shamelessly. Trying to rid myself of the last lingering bits of shyness, I downed two bottles of mead and crossed the sobriety line. Like the gentleman he was, he helped me wobble upstairs to my rented room and made sure I was okay. I invited him to stay for a while, to talk until my head stopped spinning. He soon fell asleep with his head in my lap, recalling a story of his childhood, and I crept back downstairs to sit here and record the day's events and wait for sleep to beckon me too.<br>
-----<br>
<br>
